==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic: cognate with Old Frisian [[aga|āga]], Old Saxon [[egan|ēgan]], Old High German [[eigan]], Old Norse [[eiga]], Gothic [[𐌰𐌹𐌲𐌰𐌽]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'a:ɣan/

===Verb===
'''āgan''' (preterite-present: '''āh''' ‘he has’, '''āhst'''/'''āht''' ‘you have’, '''āgon''' ‘they have’, '''āhte''' ‘he had’)
# to [[own]], to [[possess]], to [[have]]
#:''Ah him lifes geweald.''  He has power over life.  (''Legend of St Andrew'')

===Descendents===
*English [[owe]]


